Hook Battle

by: Phillip Huang

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I chose to make this game because it is challenging to play. There is no winning or losing, but there is a highest record of the survived time, making the game competitive. I like to play a video game called League of Legends, so I made this game with League of Legend's theme.

2. What I Learned

I learned that there were many bugs that I have to fix. At the start, there were a few bugs about the timer; it was not counting the time properly. The collision boxes were not accurate; the robot dies even when it did not touch the mushroom. Moving the position of the robot is not right. The testers said i I should fix all those bugs and also use better quality of images. I also had to write the game instructions more clearly.

3. Architecture of My Game

Similar to league invaders, my game has classes that control the robot and spawn random enemies. The "Blitzcrank" class is the class that controls your main character. The "GameObject" sets the height and width for images and also collision box. "GamePanel" controls game state, menu state, and end state and determines what will happen when mouse is pressed to certain keys are pressed. It also starts and resets the timer and draw the images. "HookBattle" sets up window size and starts the game. "Mushroom" are projectiles that moves around randomly. "ObjectManager" have array lists and check collisions. "Teemo" is the hamster in the middle that only moves horizontally; mushrooms spawn based on Teemo's x and y position. "Thresh" is a random character that I added just for fun (It does not do anything).

4. Technical Implementation

I am proud of the part that I can move the robot around based on my mouse's x and y position. I am also proud of making the timer, for example I made the mushrooms spawn every second. For the robot's x and y position, I made the class "Blitzcrank" and have the character move around with a certain speed. For the timer, every time the current state is game state, i made the timer value 0 so that it resets every time I start a new game.

5. Most Challenging Part

I think the timer part was hard because I spent a lot of on it. My timer did not work properly during the early time when making the game, but with the assistances from instructors, I was able to fix those bugs so that the time records properly in seconds.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

There is a bug that happens when I start the game: the robot moves diagonally every time. Maybe I can delete the white borders of the mushroom and make the collision box more accurate. Other than that, I think my game is good. I can make it harder by making the mushrooms move toward the robot instead of moving around randomly.
